{"type":"auditAdvisory","data":{"resolution":{"id":1117870,"path":"ajv>fast-uri","dev":false,"optional":false,"bundled":false},"advisory":{"findings":[{"version":"3.1.0","paths":["ajv>fast-uri"]}],"found_by":null,"deleted":null,"references":"- https://github.com/fastify/fast-uri/security/advisories/GHSA-q3j6-qgpj-74h6\n- https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2026-6321\n- https://cna.openjsf.org/security-advisories.html\n- https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-q3j6-qgpj-74h6","created":"2026-05-08T17:15:09.000Z","id":1117870,"npm_advisory_id":null,"overview":"### Impact\n\n`fast-uri` v3.1.0 and earlier decodes percent-encoded path separators (`%2F`) and dot segments (`%2E`) before applying dot-segment removal in `normalize()` and `equal()`. This makes encoded path data behave like real `/` and `..`, so distinct URIs collapse onto the same normalized path.\n\nFor example, `http://example.com/public/%2e%2e/admin` normalizes to `http://example.com/admin`, and `equal()` considers them the same URI.\n\nApplications that normalize or compare attacker-controlled URLs to enforce path-based policy can be bypassed. A path that looks confined under an allowed prefix can normalize to a different location.\n\n### Patches\n\nUpgrade to `fast-uri` >= 3.1.1.\n\n### Workarounds\n\nNone. Upgrade to the patched version.","reported_by":null,"title":"fast-uri vulnerable to path traversal via percent-encoded dot segments","metadata":null,"cves":["CVE-2026-6321"],"access":"public","severity":"high","module_name":"fast-uri","vulnerable_versions":"<=3.1.0","github_advisory_id":"GHSA-q3j6-qgpj-74h6","recommendation":"Upgrade to version 3.1.1 or later","patched_versions":">=3.1.1","updated":"2026-05-08T17:15:11.000Z","cvss":{"score":7.5,"vectorString":"CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:H/A:N"},"cwe":["CWE-22"],"url":"https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-q3j6-qgpj-74h6"}}}
